        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# Welcome Back, James \uD83D\uDC4B\n\nIt's great to meet you. Five years of running experience tells me you know your body — and the fact that you've got physio clearance and you're ready to build again shows real patience and commitment. That's not easy after an injury setback, and it matters.\n\nBefore I hand you the full plan, I want to make sure it actually fits your life. **What does \"getting back\" mean to you right now?** Is it about reclaiming a certain distance, a race goal down the road, or simply feeling like a runner again without worrying about your foot?\n\nThat said, you asked for a comprehensive plan — so let me give you exactly that, and we can tune it together from here.\n\n---\n\n## A Few Things Worth Naming First\n\nYour physio has cleared you for **20-minute easy runs only — no speed work, walking breaks if there's any foot pain.** I'm going to honor that completely. Every session in this plan lives inside that boundary. Plantar fasciitis responds well to gradual, consistent loading — but it punishes impatience. So this plan is built around *consistency over intensity*, which is exactly the right tool right now.\n\nYour **easy pace range is 5:24–5:58/km.** Given the injury and recent low volume, I'd encourage you to live at the **slower end of that range (5:45–5:58/km)** for the first few weeks. There's no fitness to be gained by pushing the pace right now — but there's plenty to be lost.\n\n---\n\n## The Big Picture: 8-Week Return-to-Running Plan\n\n**Structure:** 3 days/week | Max 20 min/run | Saturday long run | Metric\n\n**Four phases across 8 weeks:**\n\n| Phase | Weeks | Focus |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 — Reestablish | 1–2 | Consistent easy movement, foot tolerance |\n| 2 — Consolidate | 3–4 | Extend duration toward 20 min, build rhythm |\n| 3 — Deload | 5 | Planned recovery — protect the gains |\n| 4 — Build Confidence | 6–8 | Solidify 20-min runs, prepare for next phase |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Reestablish (Weeks 1–2)\n*Goal: Consistent foot loading, no flare-ups, rebuild the habit*\n\n**Why this approach?** Plantar fascia tissue adapts slowly — roughly 6–8 weeks behind muscle adaptation. Starting conservatively and building gradually gives the tissue time to catch up with your cardiovascular fitness, which is still reasonably intact from your pre-injury base.\n\n---\n\n### Week 1\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run/Walk | 15 min @ 5:45–5:58/km. Walk 1–2 min if any foot discomfort. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run/Walk | 15 min @ 5:45–5:58/km. Same approach. |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run/Walk | 15 min @ 5:45–5:58/km. This is your \"long\" run this week — same effort, just anchoring the Saturday habit. |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~7.5–8 km**\n*(A modest step up from your recent weeks, well within safe progression)*\n\n**Key cue this week:** If your foot talks to you during a run, walk. If it's still talking after the walk break, stop and call it a successful session. Completing 15 minutes with zero flare is a win.\n\n---\n\n### Week 2\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 17 min @ 5:45–5:58/km. Walk breaks as needed. |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:45–5:58/km. Recovery day — don't chase Tuesday. |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ 5:45–5:58/km. Slight extension on your long day. |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~8.5–9 km**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Consolidate (Weeks 3–4)\n*Goal: Reach 20-minute runs consistently, build tissue confidence*\n\n**Why now?** Two weeks of symptom-free running means your plantar fascia is tolerating load. Now we extend duration — not pace — to build aerobic continuity and tissue resilience.\n\n---\n\n### Week 3\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ 5:40–5:55/km |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 17 min @ 5:45–5:58/km |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:45–5:58/km \uD83C\uDFAF |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~9.5–10 km**\n\n**Milestone:** Saturday is your first full 20-minute run. Treat it like a celebration, not a test.\n\n---\n\n### Week 4\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:40–5:55/km |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 18 min @ 5:45–5:58/km |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:40–5:55/km |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~10.5–11 km**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Planned Deload (Week 5)\n*Goal: Recover, consolidate adaptation, protect the foot*\n\n**Why a deload?** This isn't a step backward — it's where adaptation actually happens. Your body builds fitness during recovery, not during the runs themselves. Skipping this week is the most common mistake returning runners make. Every 3–4 weeks, a lighter week is non-negotiable.\n\n---\n\n### Week 5\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 15 min @ 5:50–5:58/km — genuinely easy |\n| **Thursday** | Rest or Walk | 20-min easy walk if you feel good, full rest if not |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 17 min @ 5:50–5:58/km |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~6–7 km**\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — Build Confidence (Weeks 6–8)\n*Goal: Solidify 20-min runs, prepare for a conversation with your physio about next steps*\n\n**Why \"confidence\"?** At this point, the goal isn't more volume — it's consistency and trust. Three solid 20-minute runs per week, symptom-free, is the foundation your physio needs to see before clearing you for longer runs or any intensity work.\n\n---\n\n### Week 6\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:55/km |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:45–5:58/km |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:50/km |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~10.5–11.5 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 7\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:50/km |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:45–5:55/km |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:50/km |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~11–12 km**\n\n---\n\n### Week 8 — Checkpoint Week\n\n| Day | Session | Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Tuesday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:50/km |\n| **Thursday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:45–5:55/km |\n| **Saturday** | Easy Run | 20 min @ 5:35–5:50/km |\n\n**Weekly volume: ~11–12 km**\n\n**End of Week 8:** Schedule a check-in with your physio. If you've completed this block symptom-free, you'll have a strong case for extending run duration and eventually reintroducing structured training toward a race goal.\n\n---\n\n## Pacing Reference Card\n\n| Pace Zone | Range | When Used |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Easy (conservative)** | 5:45–5:58/km | Weeks 1–2, deload, any foot discomfort |\n| **Easy (standard)** | 5:24–5:44/km | Weeks 6–8 when feeling strong |\n| **Speed work** | — | **Not until physio clears you** |\n\n---\n\n## Daily Foot Check Protocol\n\nBefore every run, ask yourself:\n- **0–2/10 pain or stiffness:** Run as planned\n- **3–4/10:** Shorten by 5 min, include walk breaks\n- **5+/10:** Rest day. This is the right call, not a failure.\n\nMorning stiffness in the first few steps is common with plantar fasciitis and doesn't automatically mean you can't run — but if it doesn't ease within 5–10 minutes of moving around, give it the day.\n\n---\n\n## What This Plan Doesn't Include (Yet)\n\n- ❌ Threshold or interval work — not until physio clearance\n- ❌ Runs beyond 20 minutes — same reason\n- ❌ Fourth run days — recovery is part of the plan\n- ❌ Redistributed mileage if you miss a day — just pick up where you left off\n\n---\n\n## A Note on Your Fitness\n\nYour pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 (from your 44:00 10K) is a solid benchmark. You haven't lost that — it's banked. Right now we're not training your cardiovascular system so much as we're *reintroducing load to your foot* and rebuilding the habit of consistent running. The fitness will come back faster than you expect once you're fully cleared. Patience now is the fastest route back.\n\n---\n\n**Your first step:** How does Week 1 look against your actual schedule? And is there anything about how your foot has been feeling lately that I should know before you lace up for that first Tuesday run?"
        }
